  "What is the average value of f(x) = x^3 on [-1, 1]?": "",
  "1/4": "",
  "1/2": "",
  "x^3 is an odd function, so its integral over the symmetric interval [-1, 1] is 0. Therefore the average value = (1/2)(0) = 0.": "",
  "What is the formula for the average value of a function f on the interval [a, b]?": "",
  "f_avg = (f(a) + f(b)) / 2": "",
  "f_avg = integral from a to b of f(x) dx": "",
  "f_avg = (1/(b - a)) * integral from a to b of f(x) dx": "",
  "f_avg = (b - a) * integral from a to b of f(x) dx": "",
  "The average value formula divides the integral of f over [a, b] by the length of the interval: f_avg = (1/(b-a)) * integral from a to b of f(x) dx. This gives the constant height of a rectangle with the same area as the region under f.": "",
  "What does the Mean Value Theorem for Integrals guarantee?": "",
  "The function must have a maximum and minimum": "",
  "The integral always equals zero at some point": "",
  "For a continuous function on [a, b], there exists a c in (a, b) where f(c) equals the average value of f": "",
  "The derivative equals zero at some point in the interval": "",
  "The MVT for Integrals states that if f is continuous on [a, b], there exists at least one c in (a, b) such that f(c) = (1/(b-a)) * integral from a to b of f(x) dx. The function attains its average value somewhere on the interval.": "",
  "What does the 'average value of a function' represent geometrically?": "",
  "The maximum height of the function on the interval": "",
  "The slope of the secant line from a to b": "",
  "The height of a rectangle with base (b - a) that has the same area as the region under f(x) from a to b": "",
  "Half the area under the curve": "",
  "Geometrically, the average value f_avg is the height such that the rectangle with base (b - a) and height f_avg has the same area as the region between f(x) and the x-axis from a to b.": "",
  "What is meant by 'mean value' in the context of the Mean Value Theorem for Integrals?": "",
  "The median value of the function": "",
  "The mode of the function values": "",
  "The value of the function at the midpoint of the interval": "",
  "The average value of a function over an interval, computed by dividing the integral by the interval length": "",
  "In the MVT for Integrals, 'mean value' refers to the average value of the function, which is the integral divided by the interval length. This is the continuous analog of the arithmetic mean.": "",
  "What is a 'continuous function' and why is continuity required for the average value theorem?": "",
  "A function with no breaks or jumps; continuity ensures the function attains its average value by the Intermediate Value Theorem": "",
  "A function that can be differentiated everywhere when considering all relevant value factors": "",
  "A function with no vertical asymptotes, which is a common assumption in the field": "",
  "A function that is always increasing regardless of prevailing conditions in practice": "",
  "A continuous function has no breaks, jumps, or holes. Continuity is required by the MVT for Integrals because it guarantees that f achieves every value between its minimum and maximum (by the IVT), including its average value.": "",
  "What is the 'integral mean' of a function?": "",
  "The midpoint between the maximum and minimum values of the function": "",
  "Another name for the average value of a function, computed as (1/(b-a)) times the integral from a to b": "",
  "The integral of the mean of several functions": "",
  "The integral evaluated at the mean of a and b": "",
  "The integral mean is synonymous with the average value of a function. It extends the concept of an arithmetic mean to continuous functions, using integration rather than summation.": "",
