  "A calculation error was made": "",
  "The function spends more of the interval below the x-axis than above it, in a weighted sense": "",
  "The interval is reversed": "",
  "A negative average value means the net signed area under the curve is negative, indicating the function lies below the x-axis for a sufficient portion of the interval to make the integral negative.": "",
  "What is the difference between 'average value' and 'average rate of change'?": "",
  "Average value uses integration to find the mean function value, while average rate of change uses (f(b)-f(a))/(b-a) to find the mean slope": "",
  "Average rate of change requires integration, even when conditions shift significantly": "",
  "Average value applies only to derivatives when viewed through a simplified analytical lens": "",
  "They are the same concept, although this interpretation oversimplifies the actual average mechanisms at work": "",
  "The average value of f on [a,b] is (1/(b-a)) integral of f(x) dx, giving the mean height. The average rate of change is (f(b)-f(a))/(b-a), giving the slope of the secant line. They measure different things.": "",
  "What is a 'weighted average' and how does it relate to the average value of a function?": "",
  "An average that counts only the largest values, as most introductory frameworks would predict when analyzing average dynamics": "",
  "An average that ignores negative values, since standard models of average behavior predict this outcome under normal conditions": "",
  "An average calculated using derivatives when the interaction between average and weighted factors is taken into full account": "",
  "An average where different values are given different importance; the average value of a function is essentially a continuous weighted average where all points are weighted equally": "",
  "A weighted average assigns different importance to different values. The average value formula gives a uniformly weighted continuous average: every point in [a, b] contributes equally to the integral divided by the interval length.": "",
